; ================================================================
; dir_proj.clanalyst — Claude's analyst notes for dir
; ================================================================
; This file is in markup.py format. Run:
;   python markup.py dir_proj.clanalyst dir_proj.json
; to apply changes. Then regenerate the listing.
;
; These are observations, hypotheses, and suggested annotations.
; Daniel's analysis takes precedence — treat this as a cheat sheet,
; not gospel. Some of this may be wrong.
; ================================================================


; ── BSS MAPPING ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
;
; Confirmed or strongly suspected:

/bss/ $00 BSS.DirPath "path number for the directory opened for reading"
/bss/ $01 BSS.CWDPath "path number for CWD (opened when -e flag set)"
/bss/ $02 BSS.NextDir "pointer to current directory path string (CR terminated)"
/bss/ $04 BSS.BufPtr "pointer to end of current token in command line"
/bss/ $06 BSS.PatPtr "pointer to wildcard pattern string (CR terminated)"
/bss/ $08 BSS.DirCount "flag: set by -c option (case-insensitive match)"
/bss/ $0B BSS.AnyFlag "OR of $0D|$0E|$0F — extended|dirs-only|files-only active"
/bss/ $0C BSS.PatFlag "set when wildcard pattern specified"
/bss/ $0D BSS.ExtFlag "set by -e or -l: extended listing mode"
/bss/ $0E BSS.DirOnly "set by -d: show only directory entries"
/bss/ $0F BSS.FileOnly "set by -f: show only non-directory entries"
/bss/ $10 BSS.ColWidth "0=single column (-s), 1=multi-column (default)"
/bss/ $11 BSS.LastCol "terminal column width (from SS.ScSiz, default 80=$50)"
/bss/ $12 BSS.ColmPos "remaining columns on current line — resets to LastCol each new line"
/bss/ $13 BSS.DENameLen "length of current filename after FCS→CR reformat"
/bss/ $17 BSS.OpenMode "I$Open/I$ChgDir mode byte — built from flags"
/bss/ $25 BSS.PathBuf "output buffer: copy of NextDir path, reformatted for display"
/bss/ $58 BSS.DEName "RBF directory entry buffer (32 bytes from I$Read)"
/bss/ $75 BSS.DENend "byte 28 of dir entry — last char of FCS name OR CR terminator"
/bss/ $76 BSS.wLSN0 "working LSN high byte (shifted from $75 before name reformat)"
/bss/ $77 BSS.wLSN1 "working LSN middle byte"
/bss/ $78 BSS.wLSN2 "working LSN low byte"
/bss/ $79 BSS.$79 "purpose unknown — cleared at init, not seen used after"
/bss/ $7A BSS.DotChar "dot-file filter char (init='.', cleared by -a to show all)"


; ── UNKNOWN BSS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
;
; $09 — match result flag: set=1 by Sub_0317 on match, cleared=0 on no match
; $0A — column wrap flag: set when filename written to current line
; $14-$16 — gap between DENameLen and OpenMode — purpose unknown
;            possibly scratch registers for Sub_0317 pattern matching
; $15 — used explicitly in Sub_0317 as a temp char storage during wildcard match
; $26-$57 — gap between PathBuf and DEName — may be part of PathBuf
;            PathBuf is written up to 255 chars (LDY #$00FF at $010B)
;            so $25 through $124 could all be PathBuf... but BSS is only $017B
;            in practice the path is short — $25-$57 covers 51 bytes

/bss/ $09 BSS.MatchFlag "Sub_0317 result: 1=match 0=no match"
/bss/ $0A BSS.ColFlag "set when at least one entry written to current output line"
/bss/ $15 BSS.PatTmp "temp char storage during wildcard pattern matching in Sub_0317"


; ── SUBROUTINE NOTES ─────────────────────────────────────────────

; Sub_0214 — Option parser
;   Called when '-' found in command line.
;   Advances X past '-', reads option letter, uppercases it, dispatches.
;   Loops back to itself after each option (handles "-els" etc).
;   Returns (RTS) on space or CR — silent accept of "- " garbage.
;   Unknown option → prints help and exits.
;
;   Dispatch table:
;     E, L → INC BSS.ExtFlag, CLR BSS.ColWidth  (extended listing)
;     S    → CLR BSS.ColWidth                   (single column)
;     D    → INC BSS.DirOnly, CLR BSS.FileOnly  (dirs only)
;     F    → INC BSS.FileOnly, CLR BSS.DirOnly  (files only)
;     X    → ADDB #4 (adds to mode byte — exec dir mode)
;     C    → INC BSS.DirCount (case-insensitive match flag)
;     A    → CLR BSS.DotChar (show dot files)
;     ?    → falls through to unknown handler

/label/ $0214 Sub_0214
/comment/ $0214
Option parser — advances past '-', reads letter, uppercases, dispatches.
/end-comment/
$0214  30 01               Sub_0214:      LEAX 1,X              

/label/ $0244 OptRTS
/label/ $0245 OptC
/label/ $0249 OptUnknown
/label/ $0256 OptX
/label/ $025A OptS
/label/ $025E OptEL
/label/ $0264 OptD
/label/ $026A OptF
/label/ $0270 OptA


; Sub_0274 — Path/pattern argument parser
;   Called when non-'-' token found on command line.
;   Saves start of token as BSS.NextDir.
;   Scans forward consuming valid path chars (alphanum, '.', '-', '_').
;   On CR or space — terminates and returns (path only, no pattern).
;   On '*' or '?' — wildcard found: saves as BSS.PatPtr, processes pattern.
;   On other — error: sets carry, exits via Loc_0451.
;
;   Pattern simplification in $02E4-$0314:
;     Collapses "**" → "*", replaces "?*" → "*?*"
;     This normalizes the pattern before matching.

/label/ $0274 Sub_0274


; Sub_0317 — Wildcard pattern matcher
;   Called with X→filename, Y→pattern (both CR terminated).
;   Recursive-style matching with '*' and '?' support.
;   Result stored in BSS.MatchFlag ($09): 1=match, 0=no match.
;   Uses BSS.PatTmp ($15) for character comparison temp.
;   Calls Sub_035F for optional case folding before comparing.

/label/ $0317 Sub_0317


; Sub_035F — Conditional uppercase
;   If BSS.DirCount ($08, the -c flag) is CLEAR, converts lowercase to upper.
;   If -c set, leaves character unchanged (case-insensitive match).
;   Wait — that's backwards from what you'd expect.
;   Re-reading: TST BSS.DirCount, BNE skip_uppercase.
;   So if DirCount NON-ZERO (flag set by -c), it SKIPS the uppercase.
;   Meaning -c PRESERVES case for comparison — case-sensitive when -c set?
;   That contradicts the help text "case insensitive filename match".
;   HYPOTHESIS: BSS.DirCount may be inverted — set=0 means case-insensitive,
;   and -c clears it rather than sets it. Need to verify against Init code.
;   OR: the help text description is from the user's perspective
;   and the internal logic is inverted. Flag for Daniel to verify.

/label/ $035F Sub_035F


; Loc_036E — Extended listing formatter (narrow mode path)
;   Reached from Loc_01FB when BSS.ExtFlag set AND ColWidth=0 (narrow/single).
;   Copies filename portion of dirMsg03 (format template) to BSS.PathBuf.
;   Then fills in: user#, date/time, attributes, sector#, file size.
;   Uses Sub_042B (byte-to-hex) and Sub_0442 (leading-space trimmer).
;   Builds complete extended listing line in BSS.PathBuf, then I$WritLn.
;
;   The format template dirMsg03:
;     "       0000/00/00 0000  dsewrewr                   "
;     Fields (by position in output buffer, U-relative):
;       $19 (25,U) — user number (2 bytes hex? divmod 100)
;       $1B (27,U) — year
;       $1D (29,U) — month  
;       $1F (31,U) — day
;       $21 (33,U) — hour:min (4 bytes)
;       $26 (38,U) — attributes (8 bits → "dsewrewr" format)
;       $2C (44,U) — sector number (3 bytes hex)
;       $3D (61,U) — file size fields
;       $47 (71,U) — file size (3 bytes)
;       $4F (79,U) — unknown (4 bytes)
;
;   Sub_041A — decimal digit formatter
;     Converts byte value to BCD-style decimal digit pair in output buffer.
;     Divides by 10 repeatedly, stores ASCII digits.
;
;   Sub_042B — byte to two hex digits
;     Splits byte into high/low nibbles, converts each to ASCII hex.
;     Calls Sub_0437 for each nibble.
;
;   Sub_0437 — nibble to hex ASCII
;     Adds $30 to nibble. If > '9', adds $07 to get A-F.
;
;   Sub_0442 — leading space trimmer
;     Scans a field for leading "space+zero" pairs and replaces with spaces.
;     Gives right-justified numeric fields a cleaner look.

/label/ $036E Loc_036E
/label/ $041A Sub_041A
/label/ $042B Sub_042B
/label/ $0437 Sub_0437
/label/ $0442 Sub_0442


; ── MAIN LOOP OVERVIEW ───────────────────────────────────────────
;
; Init ($0011):
;   1. Initialize BSS — ColWidth=1, LastCol=80, DotChar='.', clear flags
;   2. Set NextDir → cwdChar (the '.' data byte = current dir)
;   3. Parse command line loop ($002D):
;      - CR → done parsing, fall through to main body
;      - space → skip
;      - '-' → call Sub_0214 (option parser), advance X
;      - other → call Sub_0274 (path/pattern parser), advance X
;   4. After parsing:
;      a. Build open mode from flags → BSS.OpenMode
;      b. Detect terminal width via SS.ScSiz if ColWidth non-zero
;      c. I$Open directory → BSS.DirPath
;      d. I$ChgDir to directory
;      e. If extended/pattern: I$Open CWD → BSS.CWDPath ($01)
;      f. Initialize BSS.ColmPos = BSS.LastCol
;      g. If extended or multi-col: write "Directory of " header
;      h. Copy path to BSS.PathBuf, I$WritLn path
;      i. If extended: write column header lines (dirMsg02 via WritBlines)
;
; Main read loop ($0126 = Loc_0126):
;   1. I$Read 32 bytes → BSS.DEName buffer
;   2. Shift LSN from $75/$76/$77 → $76/$77/$78 (make room for CR terminator)
;   3. Skip deleted entries ($00 first byte)
;   4. Skip degenerate entries ($80 first byte → null name)
;   5. Strip high bit, compare against BSS.DotChar — skip dot entries
;   6. Count filename length, convert FCS→CR format
;   7. If pattern set: call Sub_0317 to match — skip on no match
;   8. If extended flag: call Sub_0317 for attribute filtering
;   9. If multi-column mode (ColWidth=1):
;      - If filename fits on current line: write it, pad with spaces
;      - If not: emit CR, start new line, write filename
;   10. If single-column (ColWidth=0):
;       - If extended flag: format full extended line via Loc_036E
;       - Else: simple I$WritLn of filename
;   11. Loop to $0126
;
; Error/exit ($0451 = Loc_0451):
;   - Special-cases error $D3 (end-of-file on directory) → clears B = normal exit
;   - If multi-column and something was written: emit final CR
;   - F$Exit with B as status

/comment/ $0011
Init — program entry point.
Initializes BSS, parses command line, opens directory, runs main listing loop.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $002D
Command line parse loop.
X points at OS-9 parameter string (does not include program name).
Dispatches on: CR (done), space (skip), '-' (option), other (path/pattern).
/end-comment/

/comment/ $005F
End of command line parsing.
Build BSS.AnyFlag = BSS.ExtFlag | BSS.DirOnly | BSS.FileOnly.
Then detect terminal width if multi-column mode active.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $0069
Terminal width detection via I$GetStt subcode $20 (PD.OPT offset in path descriptor).
B returned in X after TFR X,D.
Thresholds: ≥$50(80)=full, ≥$40(64)=64-col, ≥$30(48)=48-col, ≥$20(32)=32-col, <$20=disable columns.
$D0 error = non-CCIO device, also disables columns.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $00A0
Open the directory for reading.
Mode = BSS.OpenMode | $80 (read + directory bit).
/end-comment/

/comment/ $00B6
If AnyFlag set (extended or filter mode), also open CWD separately.
CWD path is the '@'+CR pair at Dat_046C — OS-9 shorthand for current execution dir.
Wait — that's execution dir (@), not current data dir (.).
For -e extended mode, the program needs file descriptor info requiring a second open.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $00C9
Initialize column position to terminal width.
If neither extended nor multi-column: skip header, go straight to read loop.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $00D3
Write "Directory of " header (15 bytes, no CR — path follows on same line).
/end-comment/

/comment/ $00E4
Copy BSS.NextDir path string to BSS.PathBuf.
If pattern flag set (-p), append '/' and pattern after path.
Then I$WritLn the full path — this is the "Directory of /dd/CMDS" header line.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $0114
If extended mode: write column headers (dirMsg02) via WritBlines.
dirMsg02 = "User # Last Modified..." header + separator line.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $0126
Main directory read loop.
Reads one 32-byte RBF directory entry per iteration.
End-of-directory detected at Loc_0451 via error $D3 from I$Read.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $0136
Shift LSN bytes one position down in BSS before reformatting filename.
Reason: FCS→CR reformat may write CR at $75 (BSS.DENend), overwriting LSN0.
After shift, LSN lives at wLSN0/1/2 ($76/$77/$78) — safe from CR overwrite.
The 32-byte I$Read call deposits a 33-byte working structure by design.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $013E
Filter pipeline for directory entries:
  $00 → deleted/empty slot — skip
  $80 → null FCS name (degenerate) — skip length count, go to Loc_014C
  strip bit 7, compare to BSS.DotChar:
    if match → dot/dotdot entry — skip (unless -a cleared DotChar)
/end-comment/

/comment/ $014C
Count filename length and convert FCS format to CR-terminated string.
FCS = last character has bit 7 set as end-of-name marker.
BCS loop continues while char < $80 (bit 7 clear).
After loop: strip bit 7 from last char, append CR at ,X.
Store length in BSS.DENameLen.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $0161
If pattern flag set: call Sub_0317 to wildcard-match filename against pattern.
Sub_035F (called inside Sub_0317) optionally uppercases for case-insensitive compare.
If no match: loop back to $0126 for next entry.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $0172
If AnyFlag set (extended or filter mode):
  Call I$GetStt on CWD path to get file attributes.
  BSS.$18 bit 7 = directory attribute bit.
  If DirOnly set:  skip non-directory entries.
  If FileOnly set: skip directory entries.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $01A4
Column layout decision:
  ColWidth=0 → single column mode → branch to $01FB
  ColWidth=1 → multi-column mode → continue here
  Compare filename length against remaining column space.
  If fits: write filename, pad spaces, update ColmPos.
  If doesn't fit: emit CR, reset ColmPos, write filename on new line.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $01B0
Filename fits on current line.
I$Write the filename (not WritLn — no CR yet, more entries may follow).
Compute padding: subtract filename len from ColmPos in steps of 16.
Write padding spaces from Dat_0519 (19-space pad string).
Loop back to $0126.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $01DF
Filename didn't fit — start new line.
I$WritLn cwdAndCR (just a CR byte) to terminate current line.
Reset ColmPos to LastCol (full width again).
If BSS.ColFlag set (something was on this line before): loop to pad logic.
Otherwise loop to $0126.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $01FB
Single-column narrow mode entry point.
Reached when ColWidth=0 (set by -s, or forced by narrow terminal).
If ExtFlag set → format full extended line via Loc_036E.
If ExtFlag clear → simple I$WritLn of filename (30 bytes).
/end-comment/

/comment/ $036E
Extended listing formatter.
Reached when -e/-l AND single-column mode.
Copies filename portion from dirMsg03 format template to BSS.PathBuf.
Then fills in metadata fields by reading from file descriptor sector.
Uses wLSN0/1/2 to locate the file descriptor sector.
Field order in output: user#, date, time, attributes, sector, size, filename.
Sub_041A: converts byte to 2 decimal ASCII digits in output buffer.
Sub_042B: converts byte to 2 hex ASCII digits.
Sub_0442: strips leading "space+zero" for cleaner numeric fields.
/end-comment/

/comment/ $0451
Error/exit handler.
Error $D3 = end-of-directory (I$Read past last entry) = normal termination.
If multi-column and ColWidth still set: emit final CR to terminate last line.
F$Exit with B = 0 (normal) or error code.
/end-comment/


; ── DATA LABEL SUGGESTIONS ───────────────────────────────────────
;
; Dat_046C — the '@'+CR pair used to I$Open the execution directory.
;   @ is OS-9's shorthand for the current execution directory.
;   Only opened when extended or filter mode active (BSS.$0B set).
;   Suggest renaming: execDir

/label/ $046C execDir
/dlabel/ $046C $046E auto execDir


; ── OPEN QUESTIONS FOR DANIEL ────────────────────────────────────
;
; 1. Sub_035F case logic — does -c flag mean case-sensitive or insensitive?
;    Help text says "case insensitive" but the code skips uppercasing when
;    the flag is SET. Either the help text is misleading or the flag is inverted.
;
; 2. BSS.$14-$16 — three bytes between DENameLen and OpenMode.
;    $15 is used in Sub_0317 as PatTmp. What are $14 and $16?
;
; 3. BSS.$79 — cleared at init ($002B: CLR <BSS.$79), never seen written again.
;    May be set by a syscall return value that we're not tracking.
;
; 4. BSS.$18 — loaded at $0190 (LDA <$18) to check bit 7 for directory attribute.
;    This is at ,U+$18 relative. Is $18 a named field we should add to BSS?
;    It's inside the gap $14-$24 which is mostly unmapped.
;
; 5. Loc_0451 — the $D3 special case.
;    $D3 = 211 decimal. Is this a standard OS-9 error code for EOF on RBF?
;    Or is it an I$Read return code meaning "end of directory"?
;    Worth confirming against the OS-9 error code table.
;
; 6. WritBlines — PSHS/PULS D instead of STD/LDD.
;    The code uses PSHS A,B and PULS A,B around TFR Y,D / LEAX D,X.
;    This is because after I$WritLn, Y contains bytes written, and we need
;    that in D to add to X. There is no PSHS D instruction but PSHS A,B
;    and PSHS D produce identical postbytes ($06) — same machine code.
;
; 7. The -x option (OptX: ADDB #4) adds 4 to B.
;    B is the open mode byte. Mode $05 = O.Dir (read directory).
;    $05 + $04 = $09. What does mode $09 mean in OS-9?
;    Likely: O.Dir | O.Exec = open in exec directory instead of data directory.
